04409nam a2200577Ia 9781438474847DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384748477 a10.1515/97814384748472doi  a(DE-B1597)683360  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBL1900.C576bM29 2019eb 7aPHI0140002bisacsh04a299.5/14822231 aMa, Lin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Troubled Water of Shifei :bFrom Disputation to Walking-Two-Roads in the Zhuangzi /cJaap van Brakel, Lin Ma. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (308 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 1  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Chinese Philosophy and Culture00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Referencing -- tIntroduction -- tPreliminaries -- tThe Troubled Water of Shifei -- tProjection of Truth onto Classical Chinese Language -- tDevelopmental Trajectories是非 -- tVariations of the Meaning of Shi -- tDissolution of Dichotomies of Fact/Value and Reason/Emotion -- tRightness and Fitting -- tShi and Its Opposites and Modifiers in the Qiwulun齊物論 -- tFrom Disputation to Walking-Two-Roads in the Zhuangzi -- tIs Zhuangzi a Relativist or a Skeptic? -- tZhuangzi’s Stance -- tAfterthoughts -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades, a growing concern in studies in Chinese intellectual history is that Chinese classics have been forced into systems of classification prevalent in Western philosophy and thus imperceptibly transformed into examples that echo Western philosophy. Lin Ma and Jaap van Brakel offer a methodology to counter this approach, and illustrate their method by carrying out a transcultural inquiry into the complexities involved in understanding shi and fei and their cognate phrases in the Warring States texts, the Zhuangzi in particular. The authors discuss important features of Zhuangzi's stance with regard to language-meaning, knowledge-doubt, questioning, equalizing, and his well-known deconstruction of the discourse in ancient China on shifei. Ma and van Brakel suggest that shi and fei apply to both descriptive and prescriptive languages and do not presuppose any fact/value dichotomy, and thus cannot be translated as either true/false or right/wrong. Instead, shi and fei can be grasped in terms of a pre-philosophical notion of fitting. Ma and van Brakel also highlight Zhuangzi's idea of "walking-two-roads" as the most significant component of his stance. In addition, they argue that all of Zhuangzi's positive recommendations are presented in a language whose meaning is not fixed and that every stance he is committed to remains subject to fundamental questioning as a way of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMethodology. 0aPhilosophy, Comparative. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aLiterature : Translation. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Methodology.2bisacsh1 avan Brakel, Jaap, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847484740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438474847423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438474847/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles